XDD audit extension

Nick Hoffman

2025-02-03

1 Introduction

As part of Neotoma’s participation in the Ethical Open Science for Past Global Change Data RCN, we are auditing our records for sensitive data, especially data which are sensitive with respect to the CARE principles.

The main audit document is based on programmatic searches of Neotoma metadata. These structured metadata are curated by a community of experts, so they’re a highly accurate source for making determinations about Neotoma’s holdings. However, they are necessarily limited in scope. This page documents our attempt to extend our audit through programmatic searches of the full texts of publications associated with datasets in Neotoma according to Neotoma’s metadata. This corpus is more extensive, but it is harder to draw conclusions from our hits because it is unstructured.

2 Neotoma Publications Indexed by XDD

Neotoma contains 14194 records. Of these 14194 records, only 3137 have DOIs. 7 of the DOIs are problematically formatted. Of the 3130 (22.1 %) articles with unproblematic DOIs, I searched for how many had internal document ids (XDD ids), by looping all the DOIs through the API call: https://xdd.wisc.edu/api/articles?doi=. Only 1381 (9.7 % ) publications had an internal ID with XDD. For all searches conducted so far, only publications with an internal XDD id seem to have been indexed by XDD. However, I conduct the following searches using DOI, not internal XDD ID, just in case…

Of the 3438 distinct publications associated with the FAUNMAP database, and of the the 3634 distinct publications associated with datasets of type vertebrate fauna (overlap of 3399), only 354 and 393 have DOIs associated with them, respectively. That’s 10.3 % and 10.8 % respectively, or about 0.5 of the overall percentage of Neotoma publications with a known DOI. Only 91 FAUNMAP publications (2.6 %) and 105 vertebrate publications (2.9 %) are indexed by XDD. This low percentage matters because the datasets most likely to contain sensitive data are those from the FAUNMAP database and those that concern vertebrate fauna.

4 Radiocarbon from Human Samples

As part of our interest in our repository’s relationship to CARE, we want to know about the disposition of the remains of human ancestors, for both radiocarbon dates and samples. There are 44630 records in Neotoma’s geochronology table, of which there are 7000 records ambiguous with respect to taxon (meaning the materialdated field is bone collagen, bone, blank, or NA). We would like to search for those ambiguous taxa which are most likely to be dated from human material.

We searched for all the publications in Neotoma associated with these ambiguous records and found 897 records. Of these records, only 209 have an unproblematic DOI, and 45 have an internal XDD ID.
